Lieberman Bill Would Improve Taxpayer Access To Federally Funded Research

Bipartisan bill would expand access to research,=20
greater return on taxpayer investment

WASHINGTON=97In an effort to increase taxpayers=92=20
access to federally funded research, U.S.=20
Senators Joe Lieberman (D-CT) and John Cornyn=20
(R-TX) introduced the bi-partisan Federal=20
Research Public Access Act of 2006, today.

The bill requires every federal agency with an=20
annual research budget of more than $100 million=20
to implement a public access policy. The policy=20
must ensure that articles generated through=20
research funded by that agency are made available=20
online within six months of publication.

=93We wrote this legislation to give taxpayers=20
access to scientific discoveries and advancements=20
that they are paying for,=94 said Lieberman. =93The=20
goal is to share information, avoid duplication=20
of effort and help spur new ideas which down the=20
road can mean new treatments and cures for=20
researchers, medical professionals and patients in Connecticut.=94

=93This legislation is a common-sense approach to=20
expand the public=92s access to research it funds,=94=20
Cornyn said. =93And it will help accelerate=20
scientific innovation and discovery.=94

The legislation requires these federal agencies to:

=95 Require each researcher=97funded totally or=20
partially by the agency=97to submit an electronic=20
`=A7=F7 copy of the final manuscript that has been=20
accepted for publication in a peer-reviewed journal;

=95 Ensure the manuscript is preserved in a stable,=20
digital repository maintained by that agency or=20
in another suitable repository that permits free=20
public access, interoperability, and long-term preservation; and

=95 Require that free, online access to each=20
taxpayer-funded manuscript be available as soon=20
as possible, and no later than six months after=20
its publication in a peer-reviewed journal.



